<HEADLINE>
Giant panda's home cleaned up from pollution
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
CHENGDU, May 11 (Xinhua)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Southwestern Sichuan Province has 
closed 78 mines and polluting companies in the giant panda's 
habitat to provide a better home for the endangered species, local
government said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The construction of three power stations was suspended and more
than 180 enterprises have completed technological reforms, which 
will ensure less pollution, said Cui Guangyi, deputy secretary-
general of the provincial government.
</P>
<P>
China's State Council approved the habitat of giant pandas in 
Sichuan as the sole site in the country to apply for the Word 
Heritage Natural List in 2006. The application was officially 
delivered to the World Heritage Center of the United Nations 
Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization, according to 
the provincial government.
</P>
<P>
"We hope our effort will pay off at the World Heritage Congress
to be held next year, where our application will be put to vote by
experts," said Cui.
</P>
<P>
The habitat of giant pandas in the Qionglai Mountain range in 
Sichuan will be the first to apply for the World Natural Heritage 
List, which includes Wolong Nature Reserve, Four Girls Hill and 
Jiajin Mountain, said Zhang Hu, director of the provincial working
office for world heritage sites.
</P>
<P>
Zhang acknowledged the application area, which covers 9,510 sq 
km, includes eight natural reserves and nine scenic zones. The 
area is home to about 300 wild giant pandas.
</P>
<P>
"The next step is to restore the vegetation in there areas," 
said Cui.
</P>
<P>
Giant pandas have been listed under "favorable protection" in 
Sichuan Province, which has developed 35 giant panda reserves with
habitat areas totaling 17,000 sq km, said Deng Xiangsui, director 
of wildlife protection under the provincial forestry department.
</P>
<P>
About 1,206 giant pandas live in the wild in Sichuan, 76 
percent of China's total. And 120 giant pandas live in captivity 
in the province, the most in the country, he said.
</P>
<P>
There are only 1,590 giant pandas in the wild in the world, 
mainly scattered in the mountains and hills around Sichuan Basin 
in southwestern China. There are just 160 in captivity.
</P>
